es:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Greystoke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Graystock  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Graystock","meanings":["English: locative name, from Greystoke (Cumb), recorded as  <i>Graystock</i> in 1291."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan de Greystoke was born in 1395, in Greystoke, Cumberland, England, her father, Ralph Greystoke, was 42 and her mother, Katherine de Clifford, was 42. She married Sir William Bowes about 1415, in England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1415, in Durham, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 20."},"et":{"1395–1415":"1395–1415","1387–1416":"1387–1416","1390–1436":"1390–1436","1392–Male":"1392–Surnud","1395–1465":"1395–1465","1415–1466":"1415–1466","1435–1469":"1435–1469","1353–1418":"1353–1418","1353–1413":"1353–1413","about 1381":"umbes 1381","1395":"1395","1392":"1392","1390":"1390","1415":"1415","1469":"1469","1436":"1436","1413":"1413","1435":"1435","about 1415":"umbes 1415","1466":"1466","1465":"1465","1387":"1387","1353":"1353","1418":"1418","23 April 1413":"23. aprill 1413","1416":"1416","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Greystoke, Cumberland, England":"Greystoke, Cumberland, England","Durham, England":"Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ravensworth, Yorkshire, England":"Ravensworth, Yorkshire, England","England":"England","Streatlam, Durham, England":"Streatlam and Stainton, Durham, England"},"fi":{"1395–1415":"1395–1415","1387–1416":"1387–1416","1390–1436":"1390–1436","1392–Male":"1392–Kuollut","1395–1465":"1395–1465","1415–1466":"1415–1466","1435–1469":"1435–1469","1353–1418":"1353–1418","1353–1413":"1353–1413","about 1381":"noin 1381","1395":"1395","1392":"1392","1390":"1390","1415":"1415","1469":"1469","1436":"1436","1413":"1413",